	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Elandisa Down-- Phase 3 (Gatherings)</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:Lancing_Fire@hotmail.com">Dream Chaser One</a> | 
		            2/4/2002 2:15:06 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">	In the dimly lit caverns of Luclin&#8217;s Nexus Fwyen had gone in search of her father, one of those that cared for the Faydwer Spire.  Having called for someone to handle the spire while she was away she had come to the Nexus.  Her father was surprisingly waiting for her a deep scowl on his disapproving face.  She sighed and approached him, she bowed then stood her mouth open to speak.  But he silenced her with a wave of his hand.  Around them the huge black Sphere that managed all the Spires hummed with its power while others silently went about their business.  It was quite a contrast to Norrath, where nature seemed to encourage excitement.  Here the moon kept everyone somewhat serious.  Sure the cities on Luclin abounded with fun and adventure but to Fwyen it never seemed to be as heartfelt.<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;You have something for me, my daughter?&#8221;  The question had disarmed her and kept her silent for which her father seemed pleased with since it was a rhetoric question.  &#8220;It has come to my attention that you have disregarded your duties as a Scion to journey with others.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Yes, I have father, but hear me out.  I have not abandoned them as you so think.  A great danger has arrived at Norrath, a danger that threatens Luclin and other lands away from Norrath.  A creature from beyond our heaven arrived and threatened another.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Yes the newcomers were sensed from afar, but it was your Spire that had led them to Norrath.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;M, my Spire?&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Like a beacon it pulsed and drew them to Norrath.  It was you that put us all in danger.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	Fwyen sighed, &#8220;But that is in the past and not totally my fault.  Nevertheless my greatest information isn&#8217;t that.  A Shiona&#8217;ell has been found.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;A what?  They are supposed to be wiped out.  Destroyed at Heaven&#8217;s Anvil!&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;It seems father that Shiona&#8217;ell didn&#8217;t die, but faded away.  That family line hasn&#8217;t been spoke at all since then.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;That was back when the Combine was whole.  And only then Shiona&#8217;ell went.  But this is good news, Fwyen.  You must bring this Shiona&#8217;ell to the Nexus.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Why?&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;It was Shiona&#8217;ell that brought hope to millions before.  She&#8217;ll have to do so again.&#8221;  He rubbed his sharp angled chin and smiled.  &#8220;Yes, she&#8217;ll have to come back.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	Fwyen sighed, &#8220;But we are helping the Spir&#8217;shia.  She&#8217;ll not come until later.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;We have the things that&#8217;ll help the Spir&#8217;shia, just tell her to bring it and herself.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;As you wish father.&#8221;  Fwyen left but in her heart she knew that something wasn&#8217;t right and she had felt bad about revealing the identify of Ayrryn.  Not that many would care about her being a Shiona&#8217;ell.  Norrath itself lost that identify when the Shiona&#8217;ell family disappeared millennia ago.<BR>
<BR>
*	*	*<BR>
<BR>
	Kelethin was a bustle with activity, with the Crushbone Orc always drawing adventurers to the North, with the Pixie Tricksters wreaking havoc to the west and east and commerce bursting there was no stopping the activity.  Not that Roldis cared, it was a part of him as it was them and he smiled as he approached the merchant with the potions.  As he approached he was stopped by a rough grab of his shoulder and he was spun around to face once of the huge Vah Shir.  This one was pure black one with a thick studded leather armor on his muscular body.  His huge muzzle was lined with thick whiskers and smelled highly of the forest, a pleasant smell to Roldis.<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;What is it, Limistin,&#8221; Roldis said with a pleasant smile.<BR>
<BR>
	Limistin rumbled a low growl and took Roldis&#8217; hand in his own great one.  &#8220;I have been wondering where you&#8217;ve been.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;What?  I don&#8217;t recall needing... to...  Ah, Blackened Blood!  I forgot completely!  Did you get lost or pushed back?&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Nay, I decided not to go.  You weren&#8217;t there and I was worried.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Well worried is a good word!  I did have a bit of a problem earlier today, a problem I&#8217;m helping to remedy right now.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	The large cat-man sighed, &#8220;Gambling debts?  Or perhaps you offended finally the wrong female.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Nay, none of that!  You see...&#8221; and he remembered suddenly that he couldn&#8217;t speak of it.  Even if Limistin was a good friend from way back, he wasn&#8217;t sure if it was a good thing to speak of.  He really didn&#8217;t want Fwyen to get in any trouble.  &#8220;You see I ran into a High Elven maiden and she well ran into a bunch of Orcs...&#8221; it was somewhat truthful.  &#8220;And I attempted to save her but in the fight she had been attacked by an Oracle Orc who somehow made her into a Giant of some kind.  I figured that some shrink potion might help.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Are you sure it wasn&#8217;t you that screwed up her spell casting,&#8221; Limistin said with a low rumbling laugh.  &#8220;Alright then you best get that potion to her then.  If you need me I&#8217;ll be in a tavern.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;I&#8217;ll remember it,&#8221; Roldis shook the Vah Shir&#8217;s great hand and went to the merchant.  In the distance the sun was going down and he would have to hurry.  He doubted very much that Ayrryn would appreciate sleeping outside being a High Elf and all.<BR>
<BR>
*	*	*<BR>
<BR>
	At the other side of Norrath, the Dark Elven city of Neriak sat nestled in darkness.  Loud celebration shook one section of the city, a celebration of a recent victory against a force of humans, even now the new slaves were being fitted for work.  In the darkest area of the city Icia sighed her restlessness.  She was a strikingly beautiful creature, with long jet black hair, her dark eyes shone bored through narrow eyes.  She was fit, a trained warrior on top of a good cleric, a Tier&#8217;Dal who had never grown with another nearby.  She was beyond all the words in all the languages bored.  She hated the slave driving, and the game playing with the Orcs, unlike others she had no &#8216;allies&#8217; in the cities who wished for power when the Tier&#8217;Dal claimed the lands of the Elves.<BR>
<BR>
	Many had thought that she was weak and soft but after she had beat sense in many of them they had silenced and decided that she was too aloof for those things.  She did hate those under and over her, she was better than any of them, but deep in her heart she hated the way the world ran.  She despised hiding in the dark, lying to creatures, oppressing others.  Icia was a contradiction, and in most cases she hated it.  It left her vulnerable at times, but never for long.<BR>
<BR>
	Icia stood at the entrance to the city her eyes looking beyond the darkness of the land into the heart of places she was familiar.  She had felt it though, something unnatural, something that frightened her.  She knew it held power but not a power that anyone, maybe not even the dark god.  She was tempted to leave, to go and see this power maybe even wrest it from its owner, but its mere presence frightened her.<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;You are thinking on leaving?&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	Icia spun on the voice her rapier ready to slice into the offender.  The owner of the voice was a hunched over man, his face was hidden by a cowl and only his pale blue gnarled hands indicated that he was one of her people.  He was probably a necromancer who had dabbled in the dark arts for too long.<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;What business is it of yours,&#8221; Icia hissed and sheathed her blade.  Clerics usually didn&#8217;t wield any blades longer than a dagger but she had fought to use the weapon despising the blunt edged weapons of her profession.<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;The business is the same for the Erudites, the Humans, the Trolls, and Ogres.  The business that belongs to Dwarf, Half-elf, Wood Elf, Vah Shir, Halfling.  The business of our greatest adversary the High Elves.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;You speak funny old one,&#8221; Icia said turning her eyes to the outside once more.  &#8220;And yes I am thinking of leaving this place.  I&#8217;ve been here for too long this month.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;You should though.  If not for the glory of the Tier&#8217;Dal then for your own personal glory.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;What do you know of this old one?  What is out there that I should go and be a part of?&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Outside all of Norrath unprotected by all that is Divine is a power that has been festering.  It seeks to consume everything and return creation back to nothingness.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;So what if it threatens Norrath.  Why should I care?&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;I know in your heart you despise your lot in life.  Strong and powerful you are missing something.  Though I know not what, I know that you will throw away your heritage for your own personal self.  It is not something I like but who am I?  Besides I care for Norrath, it is our home not the home of something that invades it.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	Icia sighed, &#8220;I don&#8217;t like being manipulated old one and I still see nothing in this strange play that I care to fight for.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	The old one sighed as well, &#8220;Perhaps then I shall tell you of the Heaven&#8217;s Anvil?  The powers there would craft you a weapon and armor suited for you one of your black heart.  However if you do go I would like very much to have an object made for me there.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	Icia laughed, &#8220;So I see, this journey I assume will lead me to this anvil and you want something from there.&#8221;  She laughed harder and turned on him.  &#8220;You old man have someone who will go for you!  I will bring you back what your heart desires, but I do it not for you I do it for me.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	&#8220;Good as long as that is settled.  You should know that you must go to Faydwer it is there where the journey will be joined.&#8221;<BR>
<BR>
	Icia nodded, &#8220;Then to Faydwer I go.&#8221;
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
